      "title": "Spring having mass and kinetic energy",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Spring having mass and kinetic energy</strong></h3><p>The spring of mass $\\text{m}$ and spring constant $\\text{k}$ is attached to a mass $\\text{M}$ from one end to the wall at the other end.</p><p>Assumption : spring stretches uniformly</p><p>Consider an element $\\text{dx}$ at a distance $\\text{x}$ from the fixed end. Now,</p><p>$\\frac{\\mathrm{v}_0}{\\mathrm{l}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{v}}{\\mathrm{x}} \\quad$ {as it stretches uniformly$\\}$</p><p>$\\mathrm{dm}=\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{m}}{\\mathrm{l}}\\right) \\mathrm{dx}$ {where $\\mathrm{dm}$ is the mass of element $\\}$</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"371\" height=\"133\"></p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\int _{0}^{\\text{k}}\\text{dk}=\\int _{0}^{\\text{l}}\\frac{1}{2}\\left( \\lambda \\text{dx} \\right){{\\left( \\text{x}\\frac{{{\\text{v}}_{0}}}{\\text{l}} \\right)}^{2}}$</p><p>$\\Rightarrow \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ k}=\\frac{1}{2}\\left( \\frac{\\text{m}}{{{\\text{l}}^{3}}} \\right)\\text{v}_{0}^{2}\\int _{0}^{\\text{l}}{{\\text{x}}^{2}}\\text{dx}=\\frac{1}{6}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ mv}_{0}^{2}$</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ k}=\\frac{1}{2}\\left( \\frac{\\text{m}}{3} \\right)\\text{v}_{0}^{2}$</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$ You can consider a mass of $\\left( \\frac{\\text{m}}{3} \\right)$ attached to mass in spring of mass $\\text{m}$; and then&nbsp;<br>treat it as a simple light spring problem.</p><p>Remember, $\\left( \\frac{{{\\text{v}}_{0}}}{\\text{l}} \\right)=\\left( \\frac{\\text{v}}{\\text{x}} \\right)$ obtained only when spring stretch uniformly.</p><p>(2) When the other end of the spring is not fixed :</p><p>$\\frac{\\left(\\mathrm{v}_2-\\mathrm{v}_1\\right)}{\\mathrm{l}}=\\frac{\\left(\\mathrm{v}-\\mathrm{v}_1\\right)}{\\mathrm{x}}$</p><p>$\\mathrm{v}=\\mathrm{v}_1+\\frac{\\mathrm{x}}{\\mathrm{l}}\\left(\\mathrm{v}_2-\\mathrm{v}_1\\right)$</p><p>$\\int_0^{\\mathrm{K}} \\mathrm{dK}=\\int_0^1 \\frac{1}{2}(\\lambda \\mathrm{dx})\\left[\\mathrm{v}_1+\\frac{\\mathrm{x}}{\\mathrm{l}}\\left(\\mathrm{v}_2-\\mathrm{v}_1\\right)\\right]^2$</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"380\" height=\"112\"></p><p>Hence $\\text{K}$ can be solved accordingly.</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0db29c03b9dcaf1afe06b"
    }
  ],
